'''Fort Binġemma''' (formerly written as '''Fort Bin Jema'''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pearson|first1=Owen|title=Albania in the Twentieth Century, A History: Volume III: Albania as Dictatorship and Democracy, 1945-99|date=2006|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=9781845111052|page=441|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=D4wx7kQp4bgC&pg=PA441&lpg=PA441#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> or '''Fort Bengemma''',<ref>{{cite book|last1=Castillo|first1=Dennis Angelo|title=The Maltese Cross: A Strategic History of Malta|date=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=0313323291|page=135|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=i5ns5LNtoiUC&pg=PA135#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> {{lang-mt|Il-Fortizza ta' Binġemma}}) is a [[polygonal fort]] in the limits of [[Rabat, Malta]]. It was built between 1875 and 1878 by the British as part of the [[Victoria Lines]]. The fort has been illegally occupied by the Buttigieg family since 2009, who occasionally use it as a restaurant.<ref name=independent2015-05-24>{{cite news|last1=Cordina|first1=John|title=Squatters turn Fort Binġemma into illegal restaurant, family refuses compromise|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-05-24/local-news/Squatters-turn-Fort-Bingemma-into-illegal-restaurant-6736136056|accessdate=29 May 2015|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=24 May 2015}}</ref> It is set on a hill of around 590 feet above sea level. Previous to the building of the fort there use to be a Roman city or village.<ref>MacGill, Thomas (1839), [https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=bJ8NAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA126&dq=nasciaro&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwim27aE2afJAhWJ2hoKHehcChgQ6AEINzAE "A handbook, or guide, for strangers visiting Malta"], p.126-127.</ref>
==History== Fort Binġemma was built by the British as part of the [[Victoria Lines]], a line of fortifications along the northern part of Malta, dividing it from the more heavily populated south. It is one of three forts built along the lines, the other two being [[Fort Madalena]] and [[Fort Mosta]].<ref name=militarch/>
Fort Binġemma is located at the western extremity of the line, and it was first of the forts to be built, with construction taking place between 1875 and 1878.<ref name=militarch>{{cite web|last1=Spiteri|first1=Stephen C.|title=Fort Mosta|url=http://www.militaryarchitecture.com/index.php/Fortifications/fort-mosta.html|website=MilitaryArchitecture.com|accessdate=29 May 2015|date=22 October 2011}}</ref> It has an irregular shape, and is protected by a cliff face to the north and a ditch to the south. It was armed with two [[BL 6-inch Mk VII naval gun|6-inch]] and one [[BL 9.2 inch gun Mk IX–X|9.2-inch]] breech-loading guns which had an arc of fire of 210 degrees, commanding the sea to the northwest and the ridges to the northeast.
Although the Victoria Lines were abandoned in 1907, Fort Binġemma, along with [[Fort Madalena]], remained in use for coastal defence. From 1949 to about 1952, the fort was used to train Albanian insurgents fighting the [[People's Socialist Republic of Albania|communist regime]] in the [[Albanian Subversion]].<ref name=independent2015-05-24/> It later became a communications centre for the [[Royal Signals in Malta|235 Signal Squadron]].<ref>{{Cite book |first1=Cliff |last1=Lord|first2=Graham |last2=Watson |title=Royal Corps of Signals: Unit Histories of the Corps (1920-2001) and Its Antecedents |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=031WegRPmM8C&pg=PA96 |accessdate=29 May 2015 |date=September 2004 |publisher=Helion & Company Limited |isbn=978-1-874622-92-5 |page=96 }}</ref>
==Present day== In 1981, the [[Government of Malta]] leased the fort to Gaetano Buttigieg for use as a pig farm. The lease expired in 1997, but it continued to be renewed annually until 2009. After the expiry of the lease, Buttigieg and his family continued to occupy the fort illegally, despite the government having the right to evict them. In 2011, he refused to let government officials enter the fort, which was guarded by an iron gate and dogs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Government blocked from retaking Fort Bingemma|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20110414/local/government-blocked-from-retaking-fort-bingemma.360225|accessdate=29 May 2015|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=14 April 2011}}</ref>
Illegal development took place within the fort in 2013. In 2015, it was revealed that the fort was occasionally being used as a restaurant, which is also illegal. It is also used for cows and animal farming.<ref name=independent2015-05-24/>
